b"what tactic are you referring to? if we don't know what you are talking about," b"we can't very well guard against it, can we?" b'' b'for my money (literally) i rely on a combination of a motion-detector alarm' b"with pager when i'm out of earshot of the bike in a questionable area, c&c" b'insurance, and i try to park in obvious, visible areas with lots of people' b'about. (see, if someone just plays with the bike without intention of' b'stealing it, at least some eyes are on it, and if they get too rambunctious,' b"they'll set off the alarm.)" b'' b"that's for a nice bike. for a ratbike, the trick is to always keep its" b'actual value well below blue-book, so that it looks so crappy nobody would' b'want to steal it, and even if they were stupid enough to, you would make' b'a profit on the deal. b'' b'seriously, if i (for instance) need to go on a business trip for a week,' b'and (sadly) have to leave the bikes sitting, they both get a shitty-looking,' b'but useable cover, locked on, and both bikes locked to each other and a' b'curb bumper in the parking lot under the light. i usually rig the cable' b'locks i use (aircraft cable) so that if anyone pulls on either bike or' b'the cable joining them, the concours alarm goes off. and i have a friend' b"come buy every day to have a look and make sure they're still there. the" b'only thing i have ever had stolen was a cover, and that was over' b'winter storage, with the battery out of the bike (and thus no alarm).' b'' b'oh, put your own eyelets into the cover for the locks to pass through, and' b'place them so that they have to absolutely destroy the cover to get it off.' b'' b"that's the best that i can think of. most of the locks i see people put" b'on bikes look, well, not too mechanically sound. i like abus, since i have' b'personally removed master locks from lockers with my boot.' b'' b'90 concours (mmmmmmmmmm!) beating you up, dave.' b'84 rz (ring ding) (woops!) you never learn."' b'ama dod cog (chicago) beth "bruiser" dixon' 